    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="solutionhood">KEITH asks why GROSS, unlike EDWARDS and others, sees the
achievements of science since 1580 disappearing in a haze of STS
talk.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="7" relname="span">  It would be a violation of netiquette to answer THAT
question, an even GROSSER one to say that he DOESN&apos;T,</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="8" relname="span"> BUT:.  An
answer of sorts can be found, however, INTER ALIA, in David
Stove&apos;s POPPER AND AFTER: FOUR MODERN IRRATIONALISTS.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="background">  Pergamon,
I think, around 1982. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="3" relname="background"> Apologies to whose who have read it
already. </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="3" relname="elaboration"> Alternatively, for those put off by Stove&apos;s nasty
insistence on logic alone, a look at Susan Haack&apos;s more recent,
and crystal-clear  EVIDENCE AND INQUIRY (Blackwell, &apos;92 of &apos;93)
might serve.</segment>
